<subSubSection id="6968F9DDD6684640773EA6CFF1A663CE" pageId="7" pageNumber="76" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="E587D68171C3E83D97DA372604851AE8" pageId="7" pageNumber="76">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="363276610E1A81DB286EB15BF3954D3F" pageId="7" pageNumber="76">
The name is derived from a combination of the words Patagonia and 
<taxonomicName id="287FD5B1B61684ED5312363C1B2A30D0" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Phragmatobia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Phragmatobia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Phragmatobia</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F1F33BE6E6256DEDB68227FF958A0320" pageId="7" pageNumber="76" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="BDFF52E2AEC091F884712ECEE1AAF13F" pageId="7" pageNumber="76">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DE789C3434E298132D5BC9F9FAA5419D" pageId="7" pageNumber="76">
Although 
<taxonomicName id="4401F16385BC1ACFDECABAA874E5DCB4" authority="Schmidt &amp; De Freina, 2011" authorityName="Schmidt &amp; De Freina" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Patagobia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Patagobia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Patagobia</taxonomicName>
shows similarities to the Holarctic 
<taxonomicName id="2364FC5CF2922F38590CD53475FC9180" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Phragmatobia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Phragmatobia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Phragmatobia</taxonomicName>
in some external aspects, it differs in having longer, symmetrical rami of the male antenna, ochre thoracic collar, lack of a male clasper, pale tan forewing pattern (usually), and a restricted distribution to the Chilean Andes of South America. The wing colour and pattern is also similar to 
<taxonomicName id="ECE9D4E469D6CE20E15F06019C37B2D8" authority="Schmidt &amp; De Freina, 2011" authorityName="Schmidt &amp; De Freina" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Andesobia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Andesobia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Andesobia</taxonomicName>
, but structurally 
<taxonomicName id="FA97302D826F5CB3558F97002AE3EA8B" authority="Schmidt &amp; De Freina, 2011" authorityName="Schmidt &amp; De Freina" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Patagobia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Patagobia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Patagobia</taxonomicName>
has a more robust build with denser thoracic vestiture, equally long posterior and anterior male antennal rami (anterior rami shorter than posterior in 
<taxonomicName id="9A6FCF722E37D16DA60802B210435F5C" authority="Schmidt &amp; De Freina, 2011" authorityName="Schmidt &amp; De Freina" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Andesobia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Andesobia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Andesobia</taxonomicName>
), male antennal rami up to 3 
<normalizedToken id="2B9DE32BDA7FC30C5A9A0CD41674C998" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than antennal segment length (up to 2 
<normalizedToken id="255D175E696E1E55F3F092B9AEF1DCBB" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
in 
<taxonomicName id="599B1AB148B1325A3B64E1CE9A3C8AD0" authority="Schmidt &amp; De Freina, 2011" authorityName="Schmidt &amp; De Freina" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Andesobia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Andesobia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Andesobia</taxonomicName>
); 2nd labial segment elongate, 1.8 
<normalizedToken id="DB2ABF914DC447B2CD2D435D36418153" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as wide, 1.5 
<normalizedToken id="A6AA4D5A2E4FF9941A5CE4E5D8EA1A19" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than apical segment; thoracic collar contrastingly paler ochre (conconcolourous with dorsal thoracic vestiture in 
<taxonomicName id="B58A147176EB69AB0C5CC072EEB95BCC" authority="Schmidt &amp; De Freina, 2011" authorityName="Schmidt &amp; De Freina" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Andesobia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Andesobia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Andesobia</taxonomicName>
); thoracic vestiture dense and pilose (sparse and shaggy in 
<taxonomicName id="980B13A40D9BADA36943E7EA9CBC830D" authority="Schmidt &amp; De Freina, 2011" authorityName="Schmidt &amp; De Freina" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Andesobia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Andesobia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Andesobia</taxonomicName>
);femur and tibia elongate, 4.5-5.6 
<normalizedToken id="8C826155FE62E08BEF0EE42BB41C3BCD" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than wide (very stout, 3.0-3.5 
<normalizedToken id="C0AD5A59888CB5FABE2320EC94B6C946" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than wide in 
<taxonomicName id="4355F096F26CF8D5C1DD6A0FDB25066E" authority="Schmidt &amp; De Freina, 2011" authorityName="Schmidt &amp; De Freina" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Andesobia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Andesobia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Andesobia</taxonomicName>
); metatibia with two pairs of spurs (one pair in 
<taxonomicName id="930291F3AD834FB9EAC2FB334A357806" authority="Schmidt &amp; De Freina, 2011" authorityName="Schmidt &amp; De Freina" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Andesobia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Andesobia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Andesobia</taxonomicName>
); forewing medial line present (absent in 
<taxonomicName id="B70106E12030D08FA72167A94CB56E1B" authority="Schmidt &amp; De Freina, 2011" authorityName="Schmidt &amp; De Freina" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Andesobia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Andesobia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Andesobia</taxonomicName>
); postmedial line usually double (absent in 
<taxonomicName id="CD7D9B3095DFCA9B7C03B1D84DE218E0" authority="Schmidt &amp; De Freina, 2011" authorityName="Schmidt &amp; De Freina" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Andesobia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Andesobia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Andesobia</taxonomicName>
); hindwing discal spot diffuse and elongate (sharp or absent in 
<taxonomicName id="00B79297242F59B711FC25EA89031317" authority="Schmidt &amp; De Freina, 2011" authorityName="Schmidt &amp; De Freina" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Andesobia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Andesobia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Andesobia</taxonomicName>
). The male coremata betwen the 7th and 8th sternite are moderately developed in 
<taxonomicName id="0DCE780F8F4A4331AA57F00D27B4CA77" authority="Schmidt &amp; De Freina, 2011" authorityName="Schmidt &amp; De Freina" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Patagobia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Patagobia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Patagobia</taxonomicName>
, very reduced in 
<taxonomicName id="59882E3B276B11056CAA0243CBE41CEF" authority="Schmidt &amp; De Freina, 2011" authorityName="Schmidt &amp; De Freina" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Andesobia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Andesobia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Andesobia</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F8002DE25494A86791EE56CDDA9207BC" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="77" pageId="7" pageNumber="76" type="description">
<paragraph id="4C549F89C581D8A2B1FBDC241C2C854F" pageId="7" pageNumber="76">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="25423D0F76C69F4AB881978B87B0F70D" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="77" pageId="7" pageNumber="76">
Male (female unknown). Head - vestiture dark brown to black, setae long; antenna bipectinate, ciliate ventrally; longest posterior rami 1.5-3.0 
<normalizedToken id="92FE8A1335536E35DB2D8958C003BD0D" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
segment length, longest anterior rami 1.1-3.0 
<normalizedToken id="5252176E8EF048C990B0D7CEFDE9297B" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
segment length; rami longest over middle third of antenna, decreasing in length toward base and apex; eye elliptical, 1.2-1.5 
<normalizedToken id="E236F488F9917036459A3DE43557D1C3" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as high as wide; labial palp short, not extending beyond vestiture of frons; haustellum reduced and poorly sclerotized, presumably nonfunctional. Thorax - vestiture of vertex and ventrum of thorax black brown; tegulae entirely black brown or black brown edged with yellowish brown; patagia yellowish brown or rarely black brown; leg vestiture brownish ochre, dorsum of femur yellow or red, co-varying with hindwing and abdomen ground colour; apex of prothoracic tibia with two subequal, blunt, triangular projections; mesotibia with two apical and two subapical spurs, length of apical spurs 1.5 
<normalizedToken id="9509BDDEAE0756A4EDF21B175DB0F379" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
and supapical spurs 0.6 
<normalizedToken id="BA83607D4AE788E75E1EFF9263653A10" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
tibial width at apex; two metatibial spurs, posterior spur slightly longer than anterior; metepisternum lacking microtymbals. Forewings - forewing length 12.9-13.2 mm (mean 13.1 mm; n = 4), length:width ratio averaging 2.1; ground colour pale ochre yellow but with broad, sometimes entirely confluent dark-brown transverse bands (Fig. 4c); pattern elements consisting of dark basal area and sinuous, diffuse dark-brown transverse lines (Fig. 4a) discal spot indistinct dorsally, but well defined ventrally; ventrally with bands obsolete except for marginal band. Hindwing - ground colour pinkish red or rarely yellow (Fig. 4d)
<pageBreakToken id="7BB6286F072C1EC44677CB344D7BB7DD" pageId="8" pageNumber="77" start="start">,</pageBreakToken>
with broad dark-brown marginal and costal band; well-defined brown, crescentic discal spot; similar ventrally but with discal spot better defined. Abdomen - Vestiture brownish black and pinkish red or yellow subdorsdally, ventrally with segmental margins yellowish ochre; abdomen entirely dark brown in melanic specimens (Fig. 4c). Coremata between sternites 7-8 in shallow pockets, scent scales approximately 0.5 
<normalizedToken id="59C7564606A74E27CD566BD85CAE0DBC" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as sternite length. Genitalia - highly simplified, with large, triangular, dorsoventrally flattened uncus characteristic of subtribe; uncus 1.5 
<normalizedToken id="E627AD776EF4EEA1362EEEDA2EF881AA" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than width of base, broadly joined to wide, band-like tegumen; dorsal margin of tegumen caudally recurved; valve simple and digitate, lacking processes or claspers, 1.5 
<normalizedToken id="2ECDC7ACCCEAC11D657731B35523D5DC" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as uncus-tegumen complex; vinculum semicircular, saccus v-shaped, similar in length to uncus; aedeagus large, 5-6 
<normalizedToken id="A88392E5B7276E49068BB9B980AF5878" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than wide, 2 
<normalizedToken id="991FEF48EB2026502DD2B14BC0052F60" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as width of genital capsule, curving dorsad slightly; coecum 1/10 length of aedeagus, directed slightly ventrad; vesica extremely large, diameter when inflated 2 
<normalizedToken id="42ABC6654617CAECFE71EC88C6B3ED06" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
that of genital capsule; vesica directed right-laterad, globose, finely spiculate, with poorly differentiated basal chamber and large apical chamber (Fig. 11b).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
